John Mark, I just looked at a graph presented by the Environmental Protection Agency of the U.S. Link: https://www.epa.gov/ghgemissions/us-greenhouse-gas-inventory-report-1990-2014 By the graph, it seems like the U.S. has been wiggling around 6,500 "emission" units since the 90s. There was a significant drop but, only after a gradual increase with a peak in 2007 or so. Not to mention, there doesn't seem to be any other significant drop that has placed us back at the low of 91. What do you mean by "past years," exactly? Thank you for your input, btw. I appreciate people that voice their opinions without insults. Do you believe we're keeping our emissions within this range and is such a range safe? Do we have to drop lower to keep our environment good? One thing that is definitely suggested by this is that the U.S. certainly has not increased in emissions over these years and has not played a major role in the contribution to the rising CO2 output. Check this graph: Link: https://www.epa.gov/ghgemissions/global-greenhouse-gas-emissions-data The U.S. has been wiggling but the emissions steeply increased not as a direct result of the U.S. Still, U.S. isn't entirely off the hook because the European Union still contributes 6% less than the U.S. does. The biggest question though, should we help out China and the other nations to decrease their emissions? I understand what you're saying, John. U.S. gotta look out for the U.S. but if we join the Agreement, there's a political statement being made that the U.S. hopes for a "greener" world (I don't want hotter summers). Plus, does the U.S. contribute to it indirectly? A lot of goods are outsourced from China and they make their way into the U.S. for sale. Does the U.S. bear some responsibility for the demand of such goods in that aspect?
